{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 17:15:22.477383", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network health assessment\n\nSummary / high-level conclusion\n- The network is mostly healthy at the routing and server tier (FRR/OSPF and server network appear reachable). The primary anomaly is a single access host (host_2_1_1_1 in 10.2.1.0/24) that has no IP address and cannot reach any infrastructure or server IPs. This is an access-layer DHCP failure localized to the router at distribution site 2 (router_dist_2_1), where the DHCP relay service is inactive.\n- Impact: host_2_1_1_1 is effectively offline (no IP), cannot obtain DHCP configuration, and therefore cannot access network services. Other hosts (e.g., host_1_1_1_1) and servers remain reachable.\n\nObserved symptoms and evidence (commands and outputs)\n1. Host host_2_1_1_1 — no IP assigned\n   - ifconfig/ip addr on host_2_1_1_1:\n     - eth0: interface is UP (RUNNING) but there is no \"inet\" entry (no IPv4 address).\n     - ip route: empty (no default route).\n   - Effect: pings from host_2_1_1_1 to other hosts/servers all show 100% loss in the reachability sweep (host_2_1_1_1 → many destinations = down).\n\n2. DHCP relay on router_dist_2_1 is inactive\n   - systemctl status isc-dhcp-relay on router_dist_2_1:\n     - Service loaded but Active: inactive (dead).\n   - router_dist_2_1 br0 is configured with 10.2.1.1/24 and OSPF advertises 10.2.1.0/24 (frr running-config shows network 10.2.1.0/24 area 1), so the router has the correct local interface but relay is not forwarding DHCP broadcasts to the central DHCP server.\n\n3. Routing and reachability beyond the distribution router appear functional\n   - router_dist_2_1 ip route and OSPF entries exist; router_dist_2_1 can ping a server in the server farm:\n     - router_dist_2_1 → web_server_0 (10.200.0.3): 4/4 replies, rtt avg ~2.59 ms.\n   - host_1_1_1_1 (other access-subnet) has a valid DHCP-assigned address (10.1.1.10/24), default gateway, and can reach DHCP server, DNS, load balancer and web servers (0% packet loss to those destinations in the sweep). This shows DHCP and routing are functional elsewhere in the network.\n\n4. Symptoms are consistent with a local DHCP forwarding failure\n   - host_2_1_1_1's interface is up but unaddressed; DHCP server is centralized (10.200.0.8) and out-of-subnet, so a relay is required. The relay service for that distribution router is stopped, so DHCP Discover messages from hosts on 10.2.1.0/24 are not being forwarded to the DHCP server — consistent with the host having no IP and being unreachable.\n\nScope and localization\n- Affected device(s):\n  - Primary affected endpoint: host_2_1_1_1 (no IPv4 address).\n  - Local network component implicated: router_dist_2_1 (DHCP relay service inactive). The access switch (switch_access_2_1_1) and the physical interface appear UP; switch br0 and eth ports show traffic counters and UP status.\n- Not affected:\n  - Other user subnet (10.1.1.0/24) and its host host_1_1_1_1 — DHCP and connectivity are fine.\n  - Server farm and inter-server connectivity — servers and load balancer are reachable from distribution routers and other hosts where expected.\n\nRoot-cause assessment\n- Most likely root cause: DHCP relay (isc-dhcp-relay) on router_dist_2_1 is disabled/inactive, preventing DHCP requests from the 10.2.1.0/24 access subnet from reaching the central DHCP server. As a result, host_2_1_1_1 never receives a DHCP lease and has no IP or default route.\n- Supporting evidence:\n  - host_2_1_1_1: interface up but no \"inet\" address, no route (DHCP presumably failed).\n  - router_dist_2_1: DHCP relay service reported \"inactive (dead)\" by systemctl.\n  - router_dist_2_1 can otherwise reach server addresses (ping to 10.200.0.3 OK), so general routing/OSPF and server-side DHCP server reachability are intact.\n\nOther observations / secondary anomalies\n- Several inter-subnet pings involving backend servers (20.200.0.x) and some web servers showed asymmetric failures in the reachability table (e.g., many backend_web_* → dns_server or → web_server_* entries appear down in the sweep). However:\n  - Most server-to-server connectivity within their expected groups (10.200.0.0/24 and 20.200.0.0/24) is healthy and load balancer / web server reachability from normal hosts (host_1_1_1_1) is OK.\n  - Some of the backend→10.200.0.x failures may be due to intended access restrictions (design states backend servers should not be directly accessible from user hosts), or they could reflect host-based firewalling or ACLs. These require separate focused checks if needed.\n- No evidence in the collected data of OSPF adjacency loss or routing table corruption on router_dist_2_1 — OSPF networks are present and the router can route to the server farm.\n\nImpact summary\n- Functional user impact: host_2_1_1_1 cannot receive DHCP address and therefore cannot use network services (cannot contact DHCP server, DNS, load balancer, web servers).\n- Network-wide impact: limited to that access subnet/host. Core/distribution routing and server availability for other subnets are not affected.\n\nActions performed (for audit)\n- Collected full reachability matrix (ping sweep) across hosts and servers.\n- Collected host network configuration for host_2_1_1_1 and host_1_1_1_1.\n- Checked router_dist_2_1 network configuration, OSPF running-config, routing table.\n- Checked isc-dhcp-relay service status on router_dist_2_1.\n- Performed pings from router_dist_2_1 to server to confirm upstream routing.\n\nSuggested further diagnostic checks (non-remediation)\n- Confirm DHCP server logs to see whether any DHCP DISCOVER messages from 10.2.1.0/24 were observed (to definitively show relay forwarding is absent).\n- Check router_dist_2_1 DHCP relay configuration file and syslog/frr logs for DHCP relay-related errors.\n- Verify switch_access_2_1_1 port statistics and ensure host is connected to the expected VLAN/subnet (it appears so, but worth confirming VLAN membership).\n- If policy requires, inspect firewall/ACL rules between backend_web and web_server subnets to explain the backend→web_server reachability anomalies.\n\nEnd of report.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 17481, "output_tokens": 2828, "total_tokens": 20309, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 17408}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1280}}}
